After “processing” all cash‐affecting events (ignoring non‐cash items and pure “transfer” entries that merely shift funds between bank and cash) and summing those cash inflows and outflows, the overall change in the company’s cash and cash equivalents comes out to be about 18,541.99. 

Below is the answer in the requested json format:

------------------------------------------------
{
  "solution": {
    "Net Increase": "18541.99"
  }
}

──────────────────────────────
Explanation (briefly): We first excluded the opening “Initial…” rows and noncash items (like depreciation and items with “Unpaid” status that did not affect cash immediately) and then computed each cash inflow (sales receipts when the receive method was “Cash”) and each cash outflow (purchases and expenses paid by cash or by bank transfer). We also disregarded internal transfers (bank‐to‐cash or cash‐to‐bank) since they do not affect the consolidated cash balance. When these items were all summed the net change came out to be an increase of roughly 18,541.99.

Note that slight rounding differences may occur but the final answer is as given above.
